  <h2>The Verse</h2>

  <div class="verse-block">
    <div class="verse-pali">
      <span class="pada">Kāmaṃ kāmayamānassa</span>
      <span class="pada">tassa ce taṃ samijjhati</span>
      <span class="pada">addhā pītimano hoti</span>
      <span class="pada">laddhā macco yadicchati</span>
    </div>
    <div class="verse-translation">
      "If it prospers for one desiring objects of desire / The fellow of course becomes exhilarated in mind, having got what he wants."
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>This is the opening verse of the Kāmasutta, the first sutta of the Aṭṭhakavagga ("Chapter of Eights"), one of the oldest texts of the Pāli Canon. The translations are from Bhikkhu Paññobhāsa, published by Path Press Publications.</p>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <h2>Word-by-Word Analysis</h2>

  <div class="word-table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Pāli</th>
          <th>Base &amp; Meaning</th>
          <th>Form &amp; Rule</th>
          <th>Root</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>kāmaṃ</td>
          <td><em>kāma</em> — desire, pleasure, sense object</td>
          <td>Accusative singular masculine. It marks the direct object of the desiring</td>
          <td class="root-cell">√<em>kam</em> — to desire, to love</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>kāmayamānassa</td>
          <td><em>kāmayamāna</em> — one who is desiring</td>
          <td>Genitive singular masculine, present middle participle (<em>-yamāna</em> suffix) in the genitive case, "of one who is in the act of desiring"</td>
          <td class="root-cell">√<em>kam</em> — to desire</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>tassa</td>
          <td><em>ta</em> — he, that one</td>
          <td>Genitive singular masculine. The pronoun referring back to the desirer; "of him"</td>
          <td class="root-cell">demonstrative pronoun</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>ce</td>
          <td><em>ce</em> — if</td>
          <td>Indeclinable particle — introduces a conditional clause; does not decline</td>
          <td class="root-cell">—</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>taṃ</td>
          <td><em>ta</em> — that, it</td>
          <td>Accusative singular masculine. Agrees with <em>kāma</em> (masculine), referring to the desired object; identical in form to neuter acc. sg. but gendered here by the subject.</td>
          <td class="root-cell">demonstrative pronoun</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>samijjhati</td>
          <td><em>samijjhati</em> — succeeds, is fulfilled, prospers</td>
          <td>3rd person singular present active with the standard present tense ending <em>-ti</em></td>
          <td class="root-cell"><em>sam</em> + √<em>idh</em> — to prosper, to succeed; <em>sam</em> intensifies</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>addhā</td>
          <td><em>addhā</em> — surely, certainly, indeed</td>
          <td>Indeclinable adverb. Adds emphasis or certainty.</td>
          <td class="root-cell">—</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>pītimano</td>
          <td><em>pīti</em> (joy, rapture) + <em>mano</em> (mind)</td>
          <td>Nominative singular. A bahubbīhi compound; does not name "joy-mind" but describes a third referent: "he whose mind is joyful." Agrees with the implied subject <em>macco</em></td>
          <td class="root-cell"><em>pīti</em> — joy, rapture; <em>manas</em> — mind, heart</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>hoti</td>
          <td><em>hoti</em> — is, becomes</td>
          <td>3rd person singular present active. From the root √<em>bhū</em>, irregular; the standard form in Pāli for "to be / to become"</td>
          <td class="root-cell">√<em>bhū</em> — to be, to become</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>laddhā</td>
          <td><em>labhati</em> — having obtained</td>
          <td>Absolutive (indeclinable). Marks an action completed before the main verb. Irregular form: <em>labh</em> + <em>tvā</em> → the consonant cluster <em>bh+t</em> simplifies by Pāli phonology to <em>dh</em>, giving <em>laddhā</em>. Because absolutives are indeclinable, asking for their "case" is not applicable — they stand invariable</td>
          <td class="root-cell">√<em>labh</em> — to obtain, to receive; same root as <em>lābha</em> (gain, profit)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>macco</td>
          <td><em>macca</em> — mortal, human being</td>
          <td>Nominative singular masculine. The grammatical subject of <em>hoti</em></td>
          <td class="root-cell">√<em>mar</em> — to die; cognate with English <em>mortal</em></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>yadicchati</td>
          <td><em>yad</em> (whatever) + <em>icchati</em> (he wishes)</td>
          <td>Relative clause — 3rd person singular present active; <em>yad</em> is the neuter relative pronoun, "whatever"</td>
          <td class="root-cell">√<em>is</em> — to wish, to desire</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
