  <h2>Syntax</h2>

  <div class="syntax-section">

    <h3>The genitive</h3>
    <p>The verse opens with two genitives: <em class="pali">kāmayamānassa</em> and <em class="pali">tassa</em>. Both refer to the subject, that is, "of one desiring desire, of him."</p>

    <h3>The conditional</h3>
    <p>The particle <em class="pali">ce</em> ("if") creates a conditional clause: <em class="pali">tassa ce taṃ samijjhati</em> — "if that succeeds for him." The <em class="pali">taṃ</em> here refers back to <em class="pali">kāmaṃ</em> and therefore agrees with it in gender: both are masculine accusative singular.</p>

    <h3>The main clause</h3>
    <p>The apodosis (the "then" half of the conditional) is: <em class="pali">addhā pītimano hoti</em> — "surely he becomes joyful-minded." The subject is <em class="pali">macco</em> ("the mortal"). <em class="pali">Pītimano</em> is a bahubbīhi compound and it functions as a predicate adjective agreeing with <em class="pali">macco</em> in the nominative.</p>

    <h3>The absolutive</h3>
    <p><em class="pali">Laddhā</em> is an absolutive: "having obtained." It expresses an action that is logically prior to the main verb (first there is obtaining, then there is the joyful state). The full verse reads: <em class="pali">laddhā macco yadicchati</em> — "having obtained whatever the mortal wishes." Here, <em class="pali">yadicchati</em> is a relative clause embedded inside this absolutive phrase.</p>

  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <h2>Grammar Reference</h2>

  <p>All nominal forms in this verse are masculine singular. The stem type here is the <em>-a</em> stem.</p>

  <h3>Masculine Singular · <em>-a</em> stem endings in this verse</h3>

  <div class="word-table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Case</th>
          <th>Ending</th>
          <th>Meaning / Function</th>
          <th>Examples here</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Nominative</td>
          <td><em>-o</em></td>
          <td>The subject — who acts or is described</td>
          <td><em class="pali">macco, pītimano</em></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Accusative</td>
          <td><em>-aṃ</em></td>
          <td>The direct object — what is acted upon</td>
          <td><em class="pali">kāmaṃ, taṃ</em></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Genitive</td>
          <td><em>-assa</em></td>
          <td>"Of" — whose story, whose concern</td>
          <td><em class="pali">kāmayamānassa, tassa</em></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>Notice that <em class="pali">taṃ</em> is the accusative of the pronoun <em class="pali">ta</em>, which shares the <em>-aṃ</em> ending with masculine <em>-a</em> stem nouns. It refers back to the masculine <em class="pali">kāma</em> and therefore agrees with it in case and gender.</p>

  <div class="grammar-grid">

    <div class="grammar-card">
      <p class="term">Present Middle Participle (<em>-yamāna</em>)</p>
      <p>Added to the present stem to mean "one who is [doing]." It declines fully like an adjective, taking whatever case its noun requires. <em class="pali">Kāmayamānassa</em> is genitive singular because it describes the desirer for whom the statement applies. Compounds with <em>-māna</em> are recurrent in Pāli.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="grammar-card">
      <p class="term">Absolutive (<em>-tvā / -itvā</em>)</p>
      <p>The absolutive is indeclinable; it has no case, gender, or number. It marks an action completed before the main verb: "having done X, then Y." When a root ends in a cluster Pāli cannot permit, phonology changes the ending: <em>labh + tvā → laddhā</em>.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="grammar-card">
      <p class="term">Bahubbīhi Compound</p>
      <p>Describes a third referent rather than naming itself. <em class="pali">Pītimano</em> = "he whose mind is joy." It points to the person, not to a thing called "joy-mind." The compound as a whole functions as an adjective, not a noun. Like English "blue-eyed."</p>
    </div>

    <div class="grammar-card">
      <p class="term">3rd Person Singular Present (<em>-ti</em>)</p>
      <p>All main verbs here are in 3rd person singular: <em class="pali">samijjhati, hoti, icchati</em>.</p>
    </div>

     <div class="grammar-card">
      <p class="term">Indeclinable Particles</p>
      <p>Indeclinables never change form. <em class="pali">Ce</em> (if) introduces a condition; <em class="pali">addhā</em> (surely) asserts certainty.</p>
    </div>

  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <h2>A Note on <em class="pali">kāma</em></h2>

  <p>The word appears twice in the first line: <em class="pali">kāmaṃ kāmayamānassa</em>. <em class="pali">Kāma</em> can mean the object of desire (a pleasure, a sense experience) or the mental act of desiring itself. The line fuses both: one who desires desire. The root √<em>kam</em> is ancient and shared across Indo-European languages.</p>

